  <div class="spaceit textReadability word-break pt8 mt8" style="clear: both; border-top: 1px solid #ebebeb;">
        <div style="float: left; display: none; margin: 0 10px 10px 0" id="score313224">
      <table border="0" width="105" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="borderClass" style="border-width: 1px;">
        <tr>
          <td class="borderClass bgColor1"><strong>Overall</strong></td>
          <td class="borderClass bgColor1"><strong>8</strong></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="borderClass" align="left">Story</td>
          <td class="borderClass">8</td>
        </tr>
                  <tr>
            <td class="borderClass" align="left">Animation</td>
            <td class="borderClass">7</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="borderClass" align="left">Sound</td>
            <td class="borderClass">8</td>
          </tr>
                <tr>
          <td class="borderClass" align="left">Character</td>
          <td class="borderClass">7</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="borderClass" style="border-width: 0;" align="left">Enjoyment</td>
          <td class="borderClass" style="border-width: 0;">8</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </div>

                          
    Overall Grade: 8<br />
Story / Pacing: 8<br />
Art / Animation: 7<br />
Sound / Music / Voice Actors: 8<br />
Character: 7<br />
Enjoyment: 8<br />
    <br />
MINOR SPOILER<br />
<br />
WORDS: ca. 800<br />
<br />
<br />
&quot;Do you want to accept this child, no matter what?&quot;<br />
<br />
This anime is criminally underrated and it feels like no one knows about it. I only got to know it through another user I know, who loves magical girls and coming of age-anime too and she recommended it to me. Then I looked here for Madoka Magica recs and found Uta Kata, decribed as a darker take on the magical girl-genre.<br />
Sadly, this wasn&#039;t released in Europe either, like many other anime unfortunately had

          <span style="display: none;" id="review313224">
        not been. <br />
<br />
<br />
ART &amp; MUSIC<br />
<br />
The art is drawn in the typical style of the mid 2000s magical girls, although it looks very pleasing and beautiful. Normally styles with big eyed girls really aren&#039;t my cup of tea, but here it&#039;s not too exeggerated. I actually like Manatsu&#039;s character design very much. Ichika and the other designs are good too. <br />
I like the color, it&#039;s fitting and colorful, but not too shiny. <br />
<br />
The opening is really beautiful and sounds good. The sound is catchy. The ending is the same and both have pretty good visuals. Although I can&#039;t remember other OSTs, to be honest.<br />
<br />
<br />
PLOT &amp; CHARACTERS<br />
<br />
The plot takes a while to develop, but the anime is only 12 episodes long, so you don&#039;t need a lot of patience to deal with the slow pacing. If you like slow pacing... good! Personally I really like the slow, but very well-included build up for the main plot. <br />
You will understand soon what the djinns and the development of her device and her personality stand for. <br />
<br />
I heard some people think, the episodic stories are boring, because they are not epic and exciting enough, although I thought that the stories felt very realistic. If you look at them from a more realistic viewpoint and put yourself in Ichika&#039;s shoes, you will recognize that, for example, losing your father&#039;s expensive watch is some kind of a &quot;daily catastrophe&quot;, especially if you are 14 year old girl. <br />
Ichika feels very believable and acts like you would expect from a girl of her age and personality type. Although I never considered that the main and side characters in Uta Kata could become some of my favorites, I still cheered for them and found them believable and likeable. <br />
<br />
Also, Ichika&#039;s parents are great people and very good parents. Maybe they come off as a little bit too good. It doesn&#039;t matter, since they fulfill their part to transport the messages of the anime. <br />
&quot;Do you want to accept this child, no matter what?&quot;, they were asked, before Ichika had been born, and then their daughter goes through a rough time in her puberty. So, I actually like this analogy there. <br />
<br />
I think some minor characters and the villain were under developed and they contributed more to the message of the anime, but they didn&#039;t appear too much like real people to me.<br />
<br />
I like that the plot slowly develops in a darker direction and includes pretty symbolism, which shows itself more clearly towards the end. <br />
In the end (I don&#039;t want to spoiler so much), it&#039;s an absolutely lovely magical girl anime about slowly growing up to a teenager, change yourself due the process and discover some darker sides of yourself and it&#039;s a story about parents supporting their child. Also, the anime has overall a lit message about self-care and self-love, which is shown in a beautiful way.<br />
<br />
The one thing I actually don&#039;t like is the misplaced fanservice in some scenes. It&#039;s not so much that it becomes unwatchable, but the girls are 14 and it&#039;s absolutely unnecessary in an otherwise lovely coming of age-anime.<br />
<br />
The other thing is that the fantasy part with the djinns also feel a little bit under developed and out of place sometimes. <br />
<br />
The ending is very metaphorical and I recommend you to watch the OVA sequel to get a satisfying conclusion. <br />
In the middle part (or before that), you will also understand what the title means.<br />
<br />
<br />
CONCLUSION<br />
<br />
Uta Kata is very beautiful coming of age anime in a magical girl setting. The anime is pretty much underrated.
        
